#X text 48 71 The ELSE library provides the [ffdelay~] object \, which is a feedforward delay line. It can also handle multi tap output with multichannels. It is quite convenience as we just use one single object instead of a write/read pair. You also don't need to bother with order of execution., f 58;
#X obj 175 336 resonant~ 500 500;
#X text 48 160 The [ffdelay~] object accepts signals to specify the delay point and also uses the same interpolation as [del.in~]. Like [del.in~] \, it can resize the delay line and freeze it. A single argument and float input value sets a single delay output. For more details \, check the help file., f 58;
#X obj 217 377 ffdelay~ -size 1000 500;
